At the local scale, 78% and 79% of all 3142 localities scored between 50 – 75 on SDGI for the years 2010 and 2015, respectively (Fig. 5
                        ). While none of the localities scored in red (below 25), 22% and 20% of the localities scored between 25 – 50 (orange) for the years 2010 and 2015, respectively. Only one locality (Kalawao, HI) in 2010 and 11 localities in 2015 scored between 75 – 100, meaning close to achieving the goal, with first rank out of 3142 localities (Fig. 6
                        ). While top 5 and bottom 5 ranking localities did not reveal enough information about distribution of these 3142 localities, but it highlights that southern localities are also in the top 5 ranks (Figs. 6 and 7
                        ).

Corresponding to states, the SDGI distribution across localities was clustered (Table 4
                        ). A few local high-high (HH) clusters were observed in the Northeastern, Midwestern, and Western regions. Conversely, low-low (LL) clusters were observed mainly in the Southern region of the country. However, high-low (HL) outliers in Southern regions, and low-high (LH) outliers in the remaining regions, were also noticeable. (Fig. 9
                        ).

Lower ECONI scores (25 – 50) are clustered in the Southern part of the country for both years (Fig. 13
                           ). This could be the result of lower scores of underlying SDGs 8, 9, and 10 in the year 2010 (Fig. 14
                           - A, C, and E). Likewise, SDGs 8 and 10 could be held accountable for the lower ECONI in southern states in the year 2015 (Fig. 14- B, D, and F). High-value clustering in the Northeastern and in between the Western (MT) and Midwestern (ND, SD) regions was consistent for both years (Fig. 13).

Likewise, the underlying SDGs 8, 9, and 10 were scored lower in the Southern localities in the year 2010 (Fig. 15
                           ), but only SDGs 8 and 10 are accountable for the lower values in the southern region in the year 2015 (Fig. 16
                           ).

Likewise, 38% and 31% of the localities in the Southern region recorded SOCI in the orange range for the years 2010 and 2015, respectively (Fig. 24
                           ). Furthermore, Fig. 25
                            confirmed the state-wise low-low clustering in the Southern region, and high values clustering in the Northeast region mainly.
